column23:
CONSENT FORM


Title of research study: Online Norm Considerations

Key information: This consent form asks you to take part in a research study. The study is being conducted by Walter Sinnott-Armstrong, PhD., associate professor at Duke University in the Department of Philosophy, the Kenan Institute for Ethics, and the Duke Institute for Brain Sciences. 

Purpose: This research study seeks to help us understand human behavior and judgment of social situations.

What you will be asked to do: This study is split in two sessions. During each session, you will be asked to complete several demographic and personality survey items. Additionally, you will be asked to give judgments for several scenarios. Each session should take less than 15 minutes. Sessions will be done two weeks apart from each other. Participation in this study is voluntary, and you can stop at any time. To stop, close your browser window.

How your confidentiality will be maintained: If you choose to participate, your name will not be linked to your responses at any time, and there is no link between this consent form and your responses. All data will be securely saved at all times. 


Future use of data: Your de-identified data (data without your name or any other identifying information), together with de-identified data from other participants in the experiment, might be made publicly available and will be shared with other researchers as a requirement of publication and funding. We may also use de-identified data for future research purposes unrelated to this project.

Benefits and risks: This research will not benefit you personally. The researcher will be happy to discuss the details of the study with you in detail at its completion. We know of no risks to you for participating in this study, however, if reading anything makes you uncomfortable, please feel free to end the study at any time. 

Compensation: You will be paid $3 for fully participating (completing all tasks and passing attention checks) in the first session, and $5 for fully participating in the second session.  

Contact: If you have any questions about this research, please email the experimenter who posted the request. You may also contact the MAD Lab at paul.mckee@duke.edu if you have any questions. You may also contact the Duke IRB office with questions or concerns with your rights as a research participant at campusirb@duke.edu. Please refer to protocol #2022-0428.

Clicking Accept: By clicking on the “I Accept” button, you indicate that you are 18 years of age or older, that you voluntarily agree to participate in this study.

column116: ih1 - 1. My ideas are usually better than other people’s ideas.
column117: ih1 - 2. For the most part, others have more to learn from me than I have to learn from them.
column118: ih1 - 3. When I am really confident in a belief, there is very little chance that belief is wrong.
column119: ih1 - 4. I’d rather rely on my own knowledge about most topics than turn to others for expertise.
column120: ih1 - 5. On important topics, I am not likely to be swayed by the viewpoints of others.
column121: ih1 - 6. I have at times changed opinions that were important to me, when someone showed me I was wrong.
column122: ih2 - 7. I am willing to change my position on an important issue in the face of good reasons.
column123: ih2 - 8. I am open to revising my important beliefs in the face of new information.
column124: ih2 - 9. I am willing to change my opinions on the basis of compelling reason.
column125: ih2 - 10. I’m willing to change my mind once it’s made up about an important topic.
column126: ih2 - 11. I respect that there are ways of making important decisions that are different from the way I make decisions.
column127: ih2 - 12. Listening to perspectives of others seldom changes my important opinions.
column128: ih3 - 13. I welcome different ways of thinking about important topics.
column129: ih3 - 14. I can have great respect for someone, even when we don't see eye-to-eye on important topics.
column130: ih3 - 15. Even when I disagree with others, I can recognize that they have sound points.
column131: ih3 - 16. When someone disagrees with ideas that are important to me, it feels as though I'm being attacked.
column132: ih3 - 17. When someone contradicts my most important beliefs, it feels like a personal attack.
column133: ih4 - 18. I tend to feel threatened when others disagree with me on topics that are close to my heart.
column134: ih4 - 19. I can respect others, even if I disagree with them in important ways.
column135: ih4 - 20. I am willing to hear others out, even if I disagree with them.
column136: ih4 - 21. When someone disagrees with ideas that are important to me, it makes me feel insignificant.
column137: ih4 - 22. I feel small when others disagree with me on topics that are close to my heart.
